{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0ce10eb-cd1a-4cb9-b651-c13b6e1930bb","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Where to look:**\n\n1. **Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```\n   /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   Core dumps are off by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n3. **Console.app** — search under \"Crash Reports\" in the sidebar for a GUI view.\n\n**Quick find command:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips 2>/dev/null | head -5\n```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is JSON and includes the signal, faulting thread, and full native backtrace — usually enough to start triaging a NativeAOT crash.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a35cc769-bdaa-4a3b-a878-e0131b21cc7a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is about crash dump collection, so let me invoke the relevant skill.","outputTokens":323},"id":"82c66ece-a521-4943-90cc-0b2e7d5cc8a5","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:59:40.489Z","parentId":"5ba4f19a-3007-46a7-92c8-dffd2515257e"}
